Use PowerShell as Administrator. This is the cleanest way.

Run:

```powershell
Rename-Item "C:\ProgramData\ssh\administrators_authorized_keys.txt" "administrators_authorized_keys"
```

Then verify:

```powershell
dir C:\ProgramData\ssh\administrators_authorized_keys*
```

You should see:

```text
administrators_authorized_keys
```

and **not**:

```text
administrators_authorized_keys.txt
```

Then fix permissions again:

```powershell
icacls.exe "C:\ProgramData\ssh\administrators_authorized_keys" /inheritance:r /grant "Administrators:F" /grant "SYSTEM:F"
```

Restart SSH:

```powershell
Restart-Service sshd
```

If `Rename-Item` says the file does not exist, run this to see the exact name:

```powershell
dir C:\ProgramData\ssh
```

Then rename the exact file you see.
